1. Title I Eligibility Ranking for San Diego Unified School District, 2019-20; BUDGETED: YES, TITLE I, PART A ENTITLEMENT
Meeting
Jan 8, 2019 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action
Fiscal Impact
Yes
Dollar Amount
$15,519,410.00
Budgeted
Yes
Budget Source
Title I, Part A Entitlement

RECOMMENDATION: Approve Title I Eligibility Ranking Plan. This report represents the 2018-19 Title I Eligibility Ranking and school participation which is used to determine the 2019-20 Title I Allocations. There are five schools (DePortola Middle, Longfellow K-8, and Spreckels, Tierrasanta, and Vista Grande elementary schools) that no longer meet the 40 percent eligibility threshold. Staff recommends these five schools be grandfathered for the 2019-20 school year. There are two schools (Henry High School and Ericson Elementary School) that were grandfathered during the 2018-19 school year, but now qualify again as their Ranking has increased over the 40 percent eligibility threshold.  Additionally, both iHigh and Standley Middle School increased over the 40 percent threshold so they will also qualify during the 2019-20 school year.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: $15,519,410.00

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: $15,500,000.00

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: The 2019-20 Title I Eligibility Rankings were discussed with the DAC at the October 17 and November 14, 2018, meetings. They were also discussed with the DAC Executive Board on October 3, November 7, and December 5, 2018. The discussions also included reviewing sites' unspent Title I balances from the 2017-18 school year.  At the November 14, 2018, General DAC Meeting the DAC voted to recommend a change in decrement to $5.00 from the current $5.50 which would result in schools with a lower meal eligibility percentage receiving additional funding.  Additional information can be found at the District Advisory Council website: DAC Website

 

BACKGROUND: The Elementary and Secondary Education Act (ESEA) of 1965 was reauthorized as of December 10, 2015, as the Every Student Succeeds Act (ESSA). Title I, one of several programs under ESSA, provides funds to schools to help disadvantaged children meet challenging academic standards. The law intends that the funds go to the district and schools that have the highest concentrations of poverty. Title I requires funding to be allocated to a district based on the number of "children in poverty" residing within the district boundary. The federal census is used to identify children ages 5 through 17 living in poverty who are included in the calculation of Title I entitlement.

 

The proposed 2019-20 Title I Ranking report allocates Title I funding to all district schools with a 2018-19 meal eligibility percentage of 40 percent or higher and the two additional schools recommended to be grandfathered. There are five schools (DePortola Middle, Longfellow K-8, and Spreckels, Tierrasanta, and Vista Grande elementary schools) that no longer meet the 40 percent eligibility threshold. Staff recommends these five schools be grandfathered for the 2019-20 school year. There are two schools (Henry High School and Ericson Elementary School) that were grandfathered during the 2018-19 school year, but now qualify again as their Ranking has increased over the 40 percent eligibility threshold. Additionally, both iHigh and Standley Middle School increased over the 40 percent threshold so they will also qualify during the 2019-20 school year.

2. Title I Supplemental Funding; BUDGETED: YES, TITLE I
Meeting
Jan 8, 2019 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action

Budgeted

Budget Source
Title I

RECOMMENDATION: Approve the Title I Supplemental Funding Plan.  This report represents a plan to provide District Level funding to schools as a Supplemental Title I allocation. This funding will be allocated to eligible school sites through the use of factors which determine higher needs of students.  These factors include Title l School Meal Eligible students and may be duplicated with one or more of the following criteria: English Learner, Chronically Absent, Homeless, Low Performing African American, or students receiving Mental Health Resource Services. These funds would be in addition to the funds received through the Title I Eligibility Ranking Plan.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: $8,211,500.00 (Title I funds).

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Based upon on-going discussions with the DAC regarding Title I funding allocations to sites, a survey was electronically distributed to all DAC representatives on December 14, 2018.  A total of 120 members responded to the survey. District staff presented and discussed the results of the survey at the December 19, 2018, DAC General Meeting. The results of the survey indicated the following: (1) Overwhelming support to increase Title I allocations to schools sites, (2) Substantial support to reduce Central Title I allocation, and (3) Substantial support to maintain Title I funds for parent involvement. A high-level, preliminary plan to reallocate more Central Title I funds to eligible school sites was shared with the DAC at the DAC General Meeting on December 19, 2018.

 

BACKGROUND: This report represents a plan to provide District Level funding to schools as a Supplemental Title I allocation. This funding will be allocated to eligible school sites through the use of factors which determine higher needs of students. These factors include Title l School Meal Eligible students and may be duplicated with one or more of the following criteria: English Learner, Chronically Absent, Homeless, Low Performing African American, or students receiving Mental Health Resource Services.

3. Graduation Strategies Implementation (Follow Up to July 24, 2018 Report of the Board Select Committee on Graduation Standards and Strategies)
Meeting
Jan 8, 2019 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Information

RECOMMENDATION: Receive staff report on the implementation of the Board Select Committee on Graduation Standards and Strategies July 24, 2018 recommendations.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Members of the Board Select Committee on Graduation Standards and Strategies were notified of this implementation report.

 

BACKGROUND: The Board Select Committee on Graduation Standards and Strategies was established in June 2017 to review the district's graduation standards and strategies and develop a comprehensive report to the Board of Education. The report, provided on July 24, 2018, offered a detailed look at the impacts of the requirement of University of California 'a-g' courses that began with the Class of 2016, their graduation success, the strategies schools used to assist in their success and the students who were not included in that success.  The report provided recommendations on ways the district can continue to provide students with more meaningful diplomas, including credit recovery, retention, student tracking and the importance of subject mastery and value.

4. Vision 2020 Quality Schools in Every Neighborhood - Report on Family and Community Engagement with Highly Regarded Neighborhood Schools that Serve Students, Families and Communities
Meeting
Jan 8, 2019 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Information

RECOMMENDATION: The Superintendent will provide an update to the board and the public on family and community engagement with highly regarded schools that serve students, families and communities (Vision 2020 Quality Indicators and corresponding LCAP Goal 5). The report includes information on the Family Engagement Team and the implementation of High Impact Home Strategies. 

 

Vision 2020 Quality Indicator Destinations:

  • All schools reach out to parents as partners in their children's education and provide parents with the information necessary to know whether their sons and daughters are on track to success.  Entire communities provide the support and resources to raise expectations and encourage students to graduate ready for success in college and careers.
  • Neighborhood schools will attract and retain a high enrollment of students in their attendance boundaries. Parents will choose the neighborhood school as a first choice because of high-quality educational programs and achievement results. Vertical clusters of schools provide continuous, integrated academic and social-emotional development programs beginning in pre-kindergarten and build at ech grade to assure that all students graduate from high school prepared to succeed in college and careers.

 

LCAP Goal 5: Families and community members are engaged and work within and across schools to support student learning. Neighborhood schools are highly regarded for their quality as well as their service as centers for extended learning and enrichment opportunities.

 

Family and Community Engagement Related Actions and Services Identified in LCAP:

  • 5.1.a.7. The Family Engagement Team will build capacity in school staffs, engage and teach community partners and family leaders to empower every family with effective home-based instructional strategies (High Impact Home Strategies and/or family learning strategies) to support their student's academic and  developmental goals.

 

BACKGROUND: At regular, public board meetings, Superintendent Marten provides a report that includes the alignment of Vision 2020, the 12 Quality Indicators, and supporting LCAP actions, services, and baseline data. Following the Superintendent's Vision 2020/LCAP report, cluster and advisory group have the opportunity to engage in dialogue on the report, and provide input and feedback on current LCAP implementation. The complete LCAP document is available on the district website at https://www.sandiegounified.org/what-lcap.

1. District Advisory Council (DAC) on Compensatory Education Semi-Annual Update to the Board
Meeting
Jan 8, 2019 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Information

RECOMMENDATION: Receive report from District Advisory Council (DAC) for Compensatory Education.  Chair, Suzy Reid, will present the Committee's semi-annual update to the board.

 

BACKGROUND: The District Advisory Council (DAC) for Compensatory Education is a district-level committee established to promote and assure the cooperative participation of parents, community members and staff in the education of children eligible for compensatory education Programs. The DAC engages in meaningful consultation on any compensatory education program changes that have not originated from the DAC. The DAC is an active participant with the community and district office responsible for categorical programs in the planning, implementation, and evaluation of compensatory education services. It is a direct means of communication and training for all compensatory education services and is a direct means of communication and training for all School Site Councils (SSC) at district schools with State and or Federal Compensatory Education Programs.

3. CORRECTED 1/8/19: Elevate Elementary Charter School: Action on Renewal of Charter Petition
Meeting
Jan 8, 2019 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.

Action

RECOMMENDATION: Staff recommends the Board approve the renewal of the charter of Elevate Elementary Charter School for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2019, and ending June 30, 2024, with the following clarifications:

 

1.  Clarification for page 130, Revise the Dispute Resolution section as detailed below:

 

Apprise the other, in writing, of the specific disputed issue(s). This written notification must identify the nature of the dispute and any supporting facts. In the event the initiating party believes the dispute relates to an issue that could potentially lead to revocation of the charter, this shall be specifically noted in the written dispute statement. Such written dispute statement may be tendered via personal delivery, facsimile, or by certified mail and will be deemed received: (a) if personally delivered, upon date of delivery to the address of the person to receive such notice if delivered by 5:00 pm or otherwise on the business day following personal delivery; (b) if by facsimile, upon electronic confirmation of receipt; or (c) if by mail, two (2) business days after deposit in the U.S. Mail. All written notices from SDUSD shall be addressed to the Executive Director at Elevate Elementary, and all written notices from the Charter School shall be addressed to the District Superintendent.  A written response shall be tendered to the other party within ten (10) business days from the date the written notification is received. If the issue is not resolved through this written communication, either SDUSD or Elevate Elementary may request a conference to discuss the claim or controversy. Within ten (10) business days of sending written correspondence, or longer if both parties agree, the Charter School Executive Director and District Superintendent, or their respective designees, shall meet and confer in an attempt to resolve the dispute. If this meet and confer fails to resolve the dispute, two representatives from each organization shall meet again at the earliest mutually convenient date to attempt to resolve the dispute.

 

2.  Clarification for page 133, Revise the School Closure Procedures section as detailed below:

 

The original cumulative files will be organized for District drop off or pick up in two categories: active students and inactive students. San Diego Unified School District will coordinate with the Executive Director or Business Manager of Elevate Elementary for the drop off or pickup of the student records and San Diego Unified School District will make all determinations for maintenance of these cumulative files after the school closure. Elevate Elementary will provide to the San Diego Unified School District a copy of student attendance records, teacher grade books, school payroll records, Title I records (if applicable), and all personnel records. All transfers of student records will be made in compliance with the Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (“FERPA”) 20 U.S.C. § 1232g. San Diego Unified School District can maintain all personnel records as long as deemed necessary. If the District will not or cannot store the records, the Charter School shall work with the County Office of Education to determine a suitable alternative location for storage.

 

3.  Clarification for page 136, Revise the School Closure Procedures section as detailed below: Revise the Oversight section as detailed below:

 

The original cumulative files will be organized for District drop off or pick up in two categories: active students and inactive students. San Diego Unified School District will coordinate with the Executive Director or Business Manager of Elevate Elementary for the drop off or pickup of the student records and San Diego Unified School District will make all determinations for maintenance of these cumulative files after the school closure. Elevate Elementary will provide to the San Diego Unified School District a copy of student attendance records, teacher grade books, school payroll records, Title I records (if applicable), and all personnel records. Pursuant to California law, the District will be required to provide oversight as required by California Education Code section 47604.32 and performance monitoring services, including monitoring school and student performance data, reviewing the Charter School’s audit reports, performing annual site visits, engaging in any necessary dispute resolution processes, and considering charter amendment and renewal requests.

 

4.  Clarification for page 139, Remove the Term and Renewal section as detailed below:

 

The proposed term of the charter will be for a period of five years from July 1, 2019 until June 30, 2024. Prior to the expiration of the charter, San Diego Unified School District, at its own will and expense, may contract an independent third-party to perform a school evaluation based upon the measurable goals and terms outlined in this charter. Elevate Elementary must submit its renewal petition to San Diego Unified School District no earlier than August 1st of the year before the charter is due to expire. Elevate Elementary and the District agree to follow the process and procedures for charter renewal as set forth in Education Code Sections 47607 and 47605, and the California Code of Regulations, Title 5, Section 11966.4.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None.

The educational program described in the Elevate charter petition includes the following characteristics:

  • Project Based Learning.

  • Stephen Covey’s “Leader in Me” program implemented schoolwide.

  • Six guiding principles serve as a framework for Elevate’s educational plan: 1) Academics, 2) Leadership, 3) Creativity, 4) Inspired Learning, 5) Global Innovators, and 6) Professional Development

Elevate is seeking renewal of its charter for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2019, and ending June 30, 2024. Staff recommends that the Board grant the charter renewal with the following clarifications as noted:

  1. Revise the Dispute Resolution section as detailed below:

     

    Apprise the other, in writing, of the specific disputed issue(s). This written notification must identify the nature of the dispute and any supporting facts. In the event the initiating party believes the dispute relates to an issue that could potentially lead to revocation of the charter, this shall be specifically noted in the written dispute statement. Such written dispute statement may be tendered via personal delivery, facsimile, or by certified mail and will be deemed received: (a) if personally delivered, upon date of delivery to the address of the person to receive such notice if delivered by 5:00 pm or otherwise on the business day following personal delivery; (b) if by facsimile, upon electronic confirmation of receipt; or (c) if by mail, two (2) business days after deposit in the U.S. Mail. All written notices from SDUSD shall be addressed to the Executive Director at Elevate Elementary, and all written notices from the Charter School shall be addressed to the District Superintendent.  A written response shall be tendered to the other party within ten (10) business days from the date the written notification is received. If the issue is not resolved through this written communication, either SDUSD or Elevate Elementary may request a conference to discuss the claim or controversy. Within ten (10) business days of sending written correspondence, or longer if both parties agree, the Charter School Executive Director and District Superintendent, or their respective designees, shall meet and confer in an attempt to resolve the dispute. If this meet and confer fails to resolve the dispute, two representatives from each organization shall meet again at the earliest mutually convenient date to attempt to resolve the dispute.

     

  2. Revise the School Closure Procedures section as detailed below:

     

    The original cumulative files will be organized for District drop off or pick up in two categories: active students and inactive students. San Diego Unified School District will coordinate with the Executive Director or Business Manager of Elevate Elementary for the drop off or pickup of the student records and San Diego Unified School District will make all determinations for maintenance of these cumulative files after the school closure. Elevate Elementary will provide to the San Diego Unified School District a copy of student attendance records, teacher grade books, school payroll records, Title I records (if applicable), and all personnel records. All transfers of student records will be made in compliance with the Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (“FERPA”) 20 U.S.C. § 1232g. San Diego Unified School District can maintain all personnel records as long as deemed necessary. If the District will not or cannot store the records, the Charter School shall work with the County Office of Education to determine a suitable alternative location for storage.

     

  3. Revise the Oversight section as detailed below:

     

    Pursuant to California law, the District will be required to provide oversight as required by California Education Code section 47604.32 and performance monitoring services, including monitoring school and student performance data, reviewing the Charter School’s audit reports, performing annual site visits, engaging in any necessary dispute resolution processes, and considering charter amendment and renewal requests.

     

  4. Remove the Term and Renewal section as detailed below:

The proposed term of the charter will be for a period of five years from July 1, 2019 until June 30, 2024. Prior to the expiration of the charter, San Diego Unified School District, at its own will and expense, may contract an independent third-party to perform a school evaluation based upon the measurable goals and terms outlined in this charter. Elevate Elementary must submit its renewal petition to San Diego Unified School District no earlier than August 1st of the year before the charter is due to expire. Elevate Elementary and the District agree to follow the process and procedures for charter renewal as set forth in Education Code Sections 47607 and 47605, and the California Code of Regulations, Title 5, Section 11966.4.

 

RENEWAL ANALYSIS

 

When considering a petition for renewal, pursuant to Title 5 of the California Code of Regulations section 11966.4(b)(1), the district governing board shall consider the past performance of the school’s academics, finances, and operations in evaluating the likelihood of future success, along with future plans for improvement, if any.

 

ACADEMICS

 

As the charter granting authority, pursuant to Education Code section 47607(a)(3)(A), the district shall consider increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils served by the charter school as the most important factor in determining whether to grant a charter renewal. For purposes of this section, “all groups of pupils served by the charter school” means a numerically significant pupil subgroup served by the charter school, as defined in Education Code section 52052(a)(3).[1]

 

Per Education Code section 47607(b), a charter school shall meet at least one of the following criteria before receiving a renewal:[2]

  1. Attained its Academic Performance Index (API) growth target in the prior year or in two of the last three years both schoolwide and for all groups of pupils served by the charter school.

  2. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API in the prior year or in two of the last three years.

  3. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API for a demographically comparable school in the prior year or in two of the last three years.

  4. The entity that granted the charter determines that the academic performance of the charter school is at least equal to the academic performance of the public schools that the charter school pupils would otherwise have been required to attend, as well as the academic performance of the schools in the school district in which the charter school is located, taking into account the composition of the pupil population that is served at the charter school.

  5. Qualified for an alternative accountability system pursuant to Education Code section 52052(h).

Assembly Bill 1808 recently amended Education Code section 52052(f) which now states:

“For any program identified in law that utilized a calculation pursuant to the former Academic Performance Index established pursuant to this section, as this section read on January 1, 2018, the 2013 growth calculation shall be applied for those purposes. For purposes of paragraphs (1) to (3), inclusive, of subdivision (b) of Section 47607, alternative measures that show increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils schoolwide and among numerically significant pupil subgroups shall be used.”

RECOMMENDATION: Staff recommends the Board approve the renewal of the charter of Harriet Tubman Village Charter School for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2019, and ending June 30, 2024, with the following clarification:

 

1. Clarification for page 11, Revise the Oversight section as detailed below:

 

Pursuant to California law, the Authorizer shall be required to provide oversight as required by California Education Code section 47604.32 and performance monitoring services, including monitoring school and student performance data, reviewing the Charter School’s audit reports, performing annual site visits, engaging in any necessary dispute resolution processes, and considering charter amendment and renewal requests. In accordance with Education Code Section 47613(a), the Authorizer may charge for the actual costs of supervisorial oversight of the Charter School not to exceed one (1) percent of the revenue of the Charter School. The Authorizer may charge up to three (3) percent of the revenue of the Charter School if the Charter School is able to obtain substantially rent-free facilities from the Authorizer. The educational program described in the Tubman charter petition includes the following characteristics:

  • The Gradual Release of Responsibility and Teach for Success instructional models are utilized schoolwide.

  • Implemented the Learning Headquarters writing program in elementary grade levels.

Tubman is seeking renewal of its charter for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2019, and ending June 30, 2024. Staff recommends that the Board grant the charter renewal with the following clarification as noted:

 

1. Revise the Oversight section as detailed below:

 

Oversight

Pursuant to California law, the Authorizer shall be required to provide oversight as required by California Education Code section 47604.32 and performance monitoring services, including monitoring school and student performance data, reviewing the Charter School’s audit reports, performing annual site visits, engaging in any necessary dispute resolution processes, and considering charter amendment and renewal requests. In accordance with Education Code Section 47613(a), the Authorizer may charge for the actual costs of supervisorial oversight of the Charter School not to exceed one (1) percent of the revenue of the Charter School. The Authorizer may charge up to three (3) percent of the revenue of the Charter School if the Charter School is able to obtain substantially rent-free facilities from the Authorizer. Pursuant to Education Code Section 47613(f), revenue of the charter school” is defined as the amount received in the current fiscal year from the local control funding formula calculated pursuant to Education Code Section 42238.02, as implemented by Education Code Section 42238.03.

 

RENEWAL ANALYSIS

 

When considering a petition for renewal, pursuant to Title 5 of the California Code of Regulations section 11966.4(b)(1), the district governing board shall consider the past performance of the school’s academics, finances, and operations in evaluating the likelihood of future success, along with future plans for improvement, if any.

 

ACADEMICS

 

As the charter granting authority, pursuant to Education Code section 47607(a)(3)(A), the district shall consider increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils served by the charter school as the most important factor in determining whether to grant a charter renewal. For purposes of this section, “all groups of pupils served by the charter school” means a numerically significant pupil subgroup served by the charter school, as defined in Education Code section 52052(a)(3).[1]

 

Per Education Code section 47607(b), a charter school shall meet at least one of the following criteria before receiving a renewal:[2]

  1. Attained its Academic Performance Index (API) growth target in the prior year or in two of the last three years both schoolwide and for all groups of pupils served by the charter school.

  2. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API in the prior year or in two of the last three years.

  3. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API for a demographically comparable school in the prior year or in two of the last three years.

  4. The entity that granted the charter determines that the academic performance of the charter school is at least equal to the academic performance of the public schools that the charter school pupils would otherwise have been required to attend, as well as the academic performance of the schools in the school district in which the charter school is located, taking into account the composition of the pupil population that is served at the charter school.

  5. Qualified for an alternative accountability system pursuant to Education Code section 52052(h).

Assembly Bill 1808 recently amended Education Code section 52052(f) which now states:

“For any program identified in law that utilized a calculation pursuant to the former Academic Performance Index established pursuant to this section, as this section read on January 1, 2018, the 2013 growth calculation shall be applied for those purposes. For purposes of paragraphs (1) to (3), inclusive, of subdivision (b) of Section 47607, alternative measures that show increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils schoolwide and among numerically significant pupil subgroups shall be used.”

BACKGROUND: On November 4, 2008, San Diego voters approved Proposition S, a school bond measure that provided $2.1 billion to improve and modernize San Diego Unified district facilities. As part of the Proposition S, and as required by law, the board appointed the Independent Citizens’ Oversight Committee (ICOC).

 

On November 18, 2008, the board took action to establish an 11 member, Proposition S ICOC that monitored how the district spent Proposition S dollars.

 

On November 6, 2012, San Diego voters approved Proposition Z, a school bond measure that provided $2.8 billion to improve and modernize San Diego Unified district facilities.

 

On February 12, 2013, the board took action to amend the Proposition S ICOC bylaws to include oversight of Proposition Z. Under the amended bylaws the consolidated committee consists of 13 members with the restriction that no member may serve more than three terms.

 

On February 10, 2015, the board amended the bylaws to reduce the number of committee members to 11. All ICOC members are selected by a vote of the board, however prior board selection members will be nominated from each of the following eight stakeholder organizations:

  • San Diego Regional Chamber of Commerce representative who is active in a business organization representing the business community located within the district
  • Middle Class Taxpayers Association representative who is active in a bona fide taxpayers’ organization
  • San Diego Unified School District Cluster Governance Committee representative who is a parent or guardian of a child enrolled in the district
  • San Diego Unified Council of PTAs representative who is a parent or guardian of a child enrolled in the district and active in a parent/teacher organization
  • San Diego Unified School District Charter School Facility Committee representative
  • American Society of Civil Engineers San Diego Section representative
  • San Diego Building and Construction Trades Council representative
  • Construction industry organization representative

As provided in the bylaws, the remaining three members shall be appointed by the board, in its sole discretion, from a list of candidates who submit applications to the district. Applications and evaluation criteria are posted on the ICOC webpage. The qualifications of all applicants are reviewed according to the evaluation criteria. The Superintendent or designee may provide input to the board on applicant qualifications.

  • One member who is active in a senior citizens’ organization
  • Two members from the community at large

On November 6, 2018, San Diego voters approved Measure YY, a school bond measure that provided $3.5 billion to improve and modernize San Diego Unified district facilities.  With the passage of Measure YY, San Diego Unified is required by state law to establish an Independent Citizens' Oversight Committee to monitor expenditures of voter approved funds.  Pursuant to the direction staff received from the Board of Education at the December 4, 2018 meeting, and recommendations received from the Proposition S and Proposition Z Independent Citizens' Oversight Committee, the Fourth Amended and Restated Bylaws establish a single  Independent Citizens' Oversight Committee to monitor bond expenditures for Proposition S, Proposition Z, and Measure YY

Subject
6. Update on the Development of the Clairemont and Lincoln Clusters, and Approval of the Purpose, Guiding Principles, and Public Information Sharing in Regard to Clusters and Cluster Councils; BUDGETED: N/A
Meeting
Jan 8, 2019 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action, Information

RECOMMENDATION: Dr. Evans and Dr. Whitehurst-Payne will provide an update on the development of the Clairemont and Lincoln Clusters, and seek Board approval of the purpose, guiding principles, and public information sharing in regard to clusters and Cluster Councils, as described below:

 

Purpose of Cluster Councils

  1. Support the academic achievement of all students in the cluster, including but not limited to, K-12 alignment implemented consistently by all schools in the cluster and the development of special themes, programs and pathways for the cluster. This goal is led by the Area Superintendent and the principals who inform the community and seek feedback.
  2. Partner with the local community for support and resources to carry out the above mission. This requires collaboration between staff and the community.
  3. Develop a unique cluster identity and promote and market the schools within the community. This requires the participation of staff and parents for a successful outcome.

 

Guiding Principle

Each cluster council will have unique characteristics and issues, based upon the circumstances of the local community. Each cluster council should be focused on the development of Quality Neighborhood Schools in its community. Each cluster council should determine its makeup and structure with participation open to administrators, classified and certificated staff, students, parents and community members. The council will determine type and frequency of cluster meetings to meet the specific goals of that cluster.

 

Note: Cluster councils are not designed to address concerns regarding individual students or teachers or personnel matters and such matters should be directed to the appropriate department. Concerns about districtwide policies should be directed to the Board of Education.

 

Public Information

In the first quarter of each academic year, the Area Superintendents should report to the Board of Education the specific goals and initiatives of the clusters they support.  The initial report on the status of clusters should be submitted within the next 30 days.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None. 

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: The original language of Vision 2020 called for the development of clusters, specifically:

  • Schools will be organized into clusters for greater community cohesion.
  • Clusters will consist of a high school and the middle and elementary schools that feed into it.
  • Clusters will ensure that there is continuity for the neighborhood students in the K-12 program.
  • Cluster councils will promote the schools in their communities.
  • Cluster councils will work with schools, community and district staff to improve the quality of their neighborhood schools.
  • Cluster councils will be a democratic representation of the school community including teachers, administrators, support staff, students, parents and community members.

1. Resolution Regarding Project Stabilization Agreement (PSA) to include Job Order Contracting and Projects that Exceed Designated Monetary Threshold and Addendum Four to PSA to Include Job Order Contracting and Projects that Exceed Designated Monetary Threshold; BUDGETED: N/A
Meeting
Jan 8, 2019 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action
Fiscal Impact
No
Budget Source
Not Applicable

RECOMMENDATION: Adopt resolution regarding the District’s Project Stabilization Agreement (PSA) to include Job Order Contracting and projects that exceed designated monetary threshold and approve the attached Addendum Four expanding the scope of the PSA to include Job Order Contracting and projects that exceed designated monetary threshold.


FISCAL IMPACT: Potential savings from utilizing cost-effective options for delivery of public works projects

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.


CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: On July 28, 2009, the Board of Education (Board) adopted a PSA and Addendum One for Proposition S School Construction, Repairs, and Renovation for projects that exceed $1 million.

 

On December 13, 2011, the Board unanimously adopted the PSA resolution and Addendum Two to extend the PSA for the duration of the Proposition S program and expand its scope to cover all projects paid for in whole or in part with state bond funds.

 

On July 24, 2012 , the Board unanimously adopted the PSA resolution and Addendum Three to expand the scope of the PSA to cover all projects that exceed $1 million, paid for in whole or in part with future local bond funds.

 

Recently passed legislation (Public Contract Code 20919.23 et seq.) authorizes a school district to utilize the Job Order Contracting (JOC) project delivery system in its construction program if it has entered into a project labor agreement that will apply to all public works awarded through JOC and to all other public works of the school district that exceed a monetary threshold set by the school district through at least December 31, 2021, regardless of what contracting procedure is used to award that work. Given that the current threshold for the PSA is over one million dollars ($1,000,000), the parties decided to designate that same threshold for the district to realize the benefits of JOC delivery method.

 

JOC allows a contractor to perform various separate job orders during the life of the contract. Contract award is based on the bid adjustment factor in which the contractor will multiply against “pre-priced” unit costs (compiled in a project ask catalog) which is part of the contract. The adjustment factor represents all of the contractor’s (indirect and direct) costs. JOC is typically used for well-defined, recurring, or repetitive work where quick execution is essential. (In the near future, staff will bring for Board approval a contract using the JOC delivery method).

 

The attached resolution and Addendum Four to the PSA extends the scope of the PSA to include projects that are awarded through JOC through at least December 31, 2021, unless further extended; and projects that exceed $1 million dollars through at least December 31, 2021, unless further extended, regardless of what contracting procedure is used to award that work and regardless of funding source.

 

Approval of this item will authorize district staff to execute the attached resolution and Addendum Four to the PSA.

BACKGROUND: The School Climate Survey for students and staff consists of The California Healthy Kids Survey and the California Staff Climate Survey which will provide data for the metrics as outlined in LCAP Goal 4: Positive School Environment, Climate and Culture – With Equity At The Core and Support For The Whole Child. 

 

The Counseling and Guidance Department will collaborate with WestEd to administer the California Healthy Kids Survey (CHKS) and the California Staff Climate Survey (CSCS) which will provide school climate data for all schools. CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: In the spring of 2018, the District and San Diego Education Association (SDEA), agreed to revise certain position descriptions and have been in negotiations since the fall of 2018.

 

The Human Resource Services Division launched a Position Description Review Project in the fall of 2015, as part of the District’s obligation to maintain the classification plan and in response to requests from the bargaining units and management team to develop a process to regularly review positions. The draft position descriptions were prepared using the data collected from employees through an online survey tool as well as management feedback. The goal of this system-wide review of classified and classified management position descriptions was to ensure that position descriptions were more than a list of tasks and duties. A well-written position description gives the reader an understanding of the basic and essential functions as well as the requisite knowledge, skills, and abilities required to perform successfully in the position. By updating position descriptions, we are able to clearly define the roles and interactions, and enhance the efficiency of the organization.

 

In addition to the Position Description Review Project, in the summer of 2016, the Human Resource Services Division, Administrators Association of San Diego, Police Officers' Association, and all three chapters of the California School Employees Association collaborated to create a joint labor-management Reclassification Committee. The Committee’s role is to accept, review, and make recommendations to the Superintendent for requests for classification review. The committee consists of one representative from each classified bargaining unit and an equal number of District representatives Reclassification Committee.

 

The classified bargaining units received the first set of draft job descriptions on April 7, 2017, the next set on September 28, 2017, and the parties have been in negotiations since that time.

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: The District currently obtains structural engineering services via the District’s architectural service agreements. However, District projects that require structural engineering services do not necessarily require architectural services. Thus, the District expends a higher rate by going through architectural services for structural engineering services that do not require an architect. In an effort to decrease structural engineering costs, the district engaged in a direct negotiation with IMEG Corp, from October 23, 2018 through November 16, 2018, to provide the District with structural engineering services.  By entering into a direct Agreement (PS19-0603-52) with IMEG Corp (formerly, “TMAD, Taylor & Gaines, Inc.”), the District will save on the 10 percent markup charged via its architectural services agreements.   IMEG Corp presented rates which are consistent with industry standards and have been determined to be cost effective over the length of the Agreement.

 

The Propositions Z and S bond program expects to continue putting in place new school facilities and facility school renovation projects. Revenues from the bond financing plan allow the District to schedule many capital facilities projects for completion over the next few years, and licensed structural engineering services will be required on an as-needed basis.

 

California Government Code section 53060, et seq., grants school districts the authority to contract with and employ persons for the furnishing of special services to such districts, if such persons are specially trained, experienced and competent to perform the special services requested.

17. CORRECTED 1/8/19: Agreement with Colbi Technologies, Inc. to Continue Providing Professional Services in Support of the Independent Citizens' Oversight Committee (ICOC) for Propositions S, Z, and Measure YY; BUDGETED: YES, GENERAL FUNDS

RECOMMENDATION: Approve Agreement with Colbi Technologies, Inc. to continue providing support for the Independent Citizens' Oversight Committee (ICOC) for Propositions S, Z, and Measure YY (PS-19-0535-24). The term of this Agreement is January 29, 2019 through January 28, 2021.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: Total not-to-exceed: $56,000.00 $66,000.00, for the two-year term of this Agreement. Budget String: 5682-00005-00-5853-8200-0000-01000-0000.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: For the period July 1, 2017 through June 30, 2018: $15,960.00.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: The District is required to establish an Independent Citizens' Oversight Committee (ICOC) to review and report to the public on the proper expenditure of taxpayers’ money for school construction, and advise the public as to whether the District is in compliance with State law in the use of all bond funds for this purpose (California Education Code section 15278, et seq.). With passage of Propositions S, Z, and Measure YY, the members of the ICOC, appointed by the Board of Education, have undertaken their responsibilities in accordance with the ICOC Bylaws approved by the Board on October 13, 2009, and as amended from time to time.

 

Education Code section 15280 (part of Proposition 39) states that the governing board of a school district shall, without expending bond funds, provide the ICOC with any necessary technical and administrative assistance in furtherance of its purpose and sufficient resources to publicize its conclusions.

 

Colbi Technologies is a trusted, consistent firm with a good reputation in the industry and has performed well for the District and the ICOC. Specifically, the ICOC relies continually on the firm’s knowledge and expertise in resolving many issues.

 

Since the current agreement expires on January 28, 2019, it is recommended a new agreement be approved to ensure the continued support necessary to meet State oversight requirements. Tasks include: (1) meeting attendance; (2) ICOC assistance with an annual review of capital bond financial and performance audits; (3) ICOC assistance with review of the deferred maintenance program and the annual Major Repair and Replacement Plan; and (4) other tasks as assigned. Colbi will bill only for those hours actually expended and authorized by the District to ensure best value and cost efficiency.

 

Government Code section 53060 allows a school district to contract with and employ any persons for the furnishing of special services if such persons are specially trained, experienced, and competent to perform the special services required.

BACKGROUND: These terminations for convenience are solely for the district's administrative convenience as an efficient way to make changes and updates, instead of executing amendments. These terminations for convenience are not a reflection of vendor performance, but rather an administrative requirement to avoid concurrent agreements with a single vendor.

 

On November 4, 2008, November 6, 2012, and November 6, 2018 respectively, residents of San Diego County voted to approve Proposition S, Proposition Z, and Measure YY (together the “Bond Program”) for capital improvement school projects. In an effort to provide a quality school in every neighborhood, the District is using Bond Program funds to repair, renovate, and revitalize District schools. Bond projects include classroom technology; safety and security upgrades; Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) upgrades; new/renovated College, Career, and Technical Education facilities; temporary classrooms replaced by permanent classrooms; air conditioning; ADA upgrades and improvements to athletic facilities; turf fields; and other capital improvements at District and charter schools throughout the District. 

 

Design services are an integral part of the construction process, and a large number of qualified firms will be necessary to provide the services required. In 2012, the District contracted with 24 architectural firms for assigned work. These agreements and amendments expire in the year and it is critical that the District maintain some capacity to issue task orders as the work progresses. The district does not possess the necessary in-house resources to perform the services.

 

On July 24, 2018, the District publicly advertised Request for Qualifications (RFQ) PS-19-0054-24 for competitive proposals. The advertisement appeared in (1) The Daily Transcript; (2) San Diego Union-Tribune; (3) San Diego Voice and Viewpoint; and (4) La Prensa San Diego. The RFQ was also posted on DemandStar and electronically bid cast to 502 vendors and forwarded to additional interested firms in the District’s Facilities Business Outreach database.

 

Thirty-five firms responded by the closing date of August 17, 2018, and were reviewed by a qualified Evaluation Committee on the basis of best value, including technical ability and price structure. Based on the final ratings of the panel, 21 firms are recommended for contract award.

 

On November 13, 2018, eight firms were recommended for contract award and now the remaining thirteen firms are presented for Board approval to complete awards to all 21 vendors. In order to execute these Agreements, the District must first terminate the existing agreements with these same firms as they cannot concurrently be party to two contracts for the same services. For this reason, these terminations for convenience are not a reflection of performance of the architects, but simply an administrative requirement for the District.

It is essential to have the architectural agreements in place for the District to complete the Bond Program. Lead times for construction projects are substantial with project design typically lasting 14 months in length after the District has issued a Notice to Proceed (NTP) to the architect, plus an additional 12 months of contract administration needed to complete each project. Design of planned projects must be commenced well in advance of when these projects are actually constructed because the designs have to be ready for bid purposes when the funds are released for construction. Design costs represent a small fraction of the cost of any construction project, but this work helps keep project costs to a minimum. Funds allocated to each contract are estimated over a three-year period, and tasks are authorized on a case-by-case basis. This process allows the District to schedule projects without delays and avoids unnecessary funding issues. Any funds remaining at term end are returned to the original source.

19. Determine that Miller Elementary and Hancock Elementary Natural Turf Fields Project is Exempt from Further Environmental Review Pursuant to California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA) Guidelines Sections 15302 (Replacement or Reconstruction) and Section 15314 (Minor Additions to Schools); Approve the Miller Elementary and Hancock Elementary Natural Turf Fields Project; Approve Agreement with Byrom-Davey, Inc. to Furnish and Install Natural Turf Field and Running Track at Miller Elementary School; BUDGETED: YES, PROPOSITION Z FUNDS

Jan 8, 2019 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action (Consent)
Fiscal Impact

Dollar Amount
$785,027.00

RECOMMENDATION: Determine that the Miller Elementary and Hancock Elementary Natural Turf Fields Project is Exempt from Further Environmental Review Pursuant to California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA) Guidelines Sections 15302 (Replacement or Reconstruction) and Section 15314 (Minor Additions to Schools).  Approve the Miller Elementary and Hancock Elementary Natural Turf Fields Project; and approve Agreement with Byrom-Davey, Inc. to furnish and install natural turf field and running track at Miller Elementary School (CZ19-0287-23). The term of this Agreement is January 8, 2019, through the completion of the Project.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: Total not-to-exceed amount: $785,027.00. Budget string: 9206-90403-00-6115-8500-0000-21400-8665.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None. 

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None. 

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: This project generally consists of the furnishing and installation of natural turf field and running track at Miller Elementary School at 4920 Carroll Canyon Road, San Diego, CA 92121.

 

Pursuant to Public Contract Code Section 20111 (b), the District must publicly competitively bid any public project involving an expenditure of $15,000 or more. The notice calling for bids was published once a week for two successive weeks in accordance with Public Contract Code section 20112.

 

Bids were due and opened on November 14, 2018. The District received a total of seven bids from Atlas Development Corporation; Blue Pacific Engineering & Construction; Byrom-Davey, Inc.; Danny Milo Corp dba DMC Enterprises; Millsten Enterprises, Inc.; Team C Construction; and Western Rim Constructors, Inc.

 

After evaluating the bids, staff determined Byrom-Davey, Inc. to be the lowest responsive and responsible bidder.

 

Additionally, consistent with the May 10, 2011, Board approved resolution in support of service-disabled, veteran-owned businesses (SDVOB) and disabled veteran business enterprises (DVBE) which established a three percent required participation of DVBE’s for all District construction contracting opportunities. The recommended contractor, Byrom-Davey, Inc. submitted a three percent DVBE participation in its bid.

 

Environmental Analysis: On June 4, 2016, the San Diego Unified School District Board of Education (Board) approved a Notice of Exemption (NOE) for both whole site modernization projects at Miller Elementary School (ES) and Hancock ES. This included the installation of a new artificial turf playfield at both schools (Exhibits 1a and 1b).

 

Due to the location of the both school sites on federal land leased from the United States Navy (USN) to the district, the WSM projects at both school sites were also subject to the National Environmental Policy Act (NEPA). The USN prepared and filed a NEPA Categorical Exclusion (CE) for both whole site modernization projects at Miller ES and Hancock ES on July 3, 2013. This project analyzed in the CE included the installation of an unspecified “turf” playfield at both school campuses (Exhibits 2a and 2b).

 

According to the CE, both school sites are located on Installation Restoration Program (IRP) Site 6, which contains Munitions and Explosives of Concern (MEC) as well as Unexploded Ordnance (UXO). As a result, an Explosive Safety Submission Determination Request (ESS DR) is required in accordance with federal regulations for all work that will involve disturbance of surface and subsurface soil. Prior to the commencement of any work, the Naval Base San Diego (NBSD) Public Works Department would be required to obtain a determination from Naval Ordnance Safety and Security Activities (NOSSA) as to whether an Explosive Safety Submission is required for the Proposed Project. In addition, the CE identifies a number of conditions pertaining to the potential presence of MECs and UXOs onsite that would need to be incorporated into the contractor bid documents and construction specifications. All final plans require approval and must receive a “Satisfactory to Proceed” signature from the NBSD Public Works Department prior to the start of any work. Compliance with these conditions will ensure that the construction activities at Miller and Hancock elementary schools would not result in any impacts related to the potential exposure of a MEC or UXO. Construction of the WSM project at each school campus, not including the turf play fields, began in the summer of 2016, shortly after the Board approval of the NOE mentioned above. Construction at each site is expected to finish in the spring of 2019.

 

Since the approval of the NOEs by the Board and the CEs by the USN, the District has elected to install natural turf field at both schools rather than artificial turf field. The Miller Elementary and Hancock Elementary Natural Turf Fields Project (Proposed Project), includes the construction a natural turf field at each school site each with a walking/running track along the perimeter of the field.

 

The Proposed Project is Categorically Exempt under the California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA) Guidelines Section(s) 15302 Replacement or Reconstruction and 15314 Minor Additions to Schools. The Proposed Project is considered exempt because:

 

1.  The Proposed Project would replace an existing use within the premises of the existing school campus;

2.  The Proposed Project would serve the existing student population and would not increase student capacity or enrollment by greater than 25 percent;

3.  The Proposed Project would not result in a net increase in classroom space greater than 10 classrooms;

4.  The area within and surrounding the project site is not environmentally sensitive; and,

5.  With compliance with the conditions set forth by the USN in the previously approved NOE and CE regarding MECs and UXOs the Proposed Project would not result in any environmental impacts.

 

Section 15300.2 of the State CEQA Guidelines specifies several exceptions to the use of a categorical exemption. These exceptions will also be used to test the use of the general rule exemption for the Proposed Project to determine, with certainty, that there is no possibility that the Proposed Project will have a significant effect on the environment.

 

a. Location. Classes 3, 4, 5, 6, and 11 are qualified by consideration of where the project is to be located – a project that is ordinarily insignificant in its impact on the environment may in a particularly sensitive environment be significant. Therefore, these classes are considered to apply in all instances, except where the project may impact on an environmental resource of hazardous or critical concern where designated, precisely mapped, and officially adopted pursuant to law by federal, state, or local agencies.

b. Cumulative Impact. All exemptions for these classes are inapplicable when the cumulative impact of successive projects of the same type in the same place, over time is significant.

c. Significant Effect. A categorical exemption shall not be used for an activity where there is a reasonable possibility that the activity will have a significant effect on the environment due to unusual circumstances.

d. Scenic Highways. A categorical exemption shall not be used for a project which may result in damage to scenic resources, including but not limited to, trees, historic buildings, rock outcroppings, or similar resources, within a highway officially designated as a state scenic highway. This does not apply to improvements that are required as mitigation by an adopted negative declaration or certified EIR.

e. Hazardous Waste Sites. A categorical exemption shall not be used for a project located on a site that is included on any list compiled pursuant to Section 65962.5 of the Government Code.

f.  Historical Resources. A categorical exemption shall not be used for a project that may cause a substantial adverse change in the significance of a historical resource.

 

The following provides review of the potential environmental issues associated with the Proposed Project to ensure that the above exceptions are not relevant to the project.

 

a. Location. The Proposed Project would occur entirely within two existing schools in urbanized areas. The area proposed for the installation of the natural turf fields are existing decomposed granite playfields and therefore are not environmentally sensitive. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the Proposed Project.

b. Cumulative Impact. There are no known future projects on the campus that when combined with the Proposed Project would result in a cumulatively considerable effect on the environment. The previously approved WSM projects at each site are currently under construction and the concurrent construction of the WSM and turf playfields were already contemplated in the previously approved NOE and CE. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the Proposed Project.

c. Significant Effect. There is no reasonable possibility that the proposed activity would have a significant effect on the environment due to unusual circumstances. The Proposed Project would serve the existing student population and would not increase the original student capacity of the school by more than 25 percent or ten classrooms, nor would the project require changes to the land use of the site. Construction would occur during the time periods allowed within the City’s Noise Ordinance.

 

Construction of the proposed improvements would not require the removal of any healthy, mature, or scenic trees. Stationary and mobile emissions generated from construction activities would be similar to or less than the previously approved project. Grading associated with the natural turf field would be less intensive than with the installation of artificial turf.

 

As mentioned above, both school sites are located on Installation Restoration Program Site 6, which potentially contains MECs as well as UXOs. However, a CE previously prepared by the USN identifies a number of conditions that must be implemented during project construction. Additionally, all final plans require approval and must receive a “Satisfactory to Proceed” signature from the NBSD Public Works Department prior to the start of any work. Compliance with these conditions will ensure that the construction of the Proposed Project would not result in any impacts related to the potential exposure of a MEC or UXO. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the Proposed Project.

 

d. Scenic Highways. The Proposed Project would not result in the demolition of existing structures or the construction of new facilities that would directly or indirectly affect an officially designated scenic highway or scenic resources near a scenic highway. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the Proposed Project.

e. Hazardous Waste Sites. A review of the EnviroStor database, maintained by the California Department of Toxic Substances, does not identify Miller or Hancock elementary schools as a hazardous waste site pursuant to Section 65962.5 of the Government Code. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the Proposed Project.

f. Historical Resources. Miller or Hancock elementary schools were built between 1975 and 1978, and therefore, do not meet the 45-year age criteria to be considered a potential historical resource. Therefore, the Proposed Project would not cause a substantial adverse change in the significance of a historical resource as defined in Section 15064.5 of the State CEQA Guidelines. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the Proposed Project.

 

Approval of this item approves the Proposed Project as described and authorizes and directs staff to file a Notice of Exemption with the San Diego County Recorder/Clerk; and approves the Agreement with Byrom-Davey, Inc. to furnish and install natural turf field and running track at Miller Elementary School. (Appendix E)

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None

BACKGROUND: In 2012, voters approved Proposition Z which included spending $350 million for charter schools/facilities. On September 4, 2012, the Board of Education (Board) passed a resolution establishing the San Diego Unified School District Charter School Facility Committee (CSFC) for the purpose of providing recommendations on the allocation of $350M of Proposition Z bond funds set aside for charter school capital facility projects.

 

On July 7, 2015, the Board approved the CSFC recommendation for a project budget of $36,312,485 of Proposition Z bond funds for Health Sciences High and Middle College (HSHMC).

 

On February 27, 2018 and July 10, 2018 the Board approved the Purchase and Sale Agreement for the purchase of 3910 University Avenue and 3995 Polk Avenue, San Diego for the intended occupancy by HSHMC. On July 20, 2018, escrow closed.

 

On July 10, 2018, the Board also approved a CEQA NOE for the purchase and use of the project site exclusively by HSHMC (Attachment 7). At the time of the approval of the NOE, it was assumed that all tenants other than HSHMC would no longer occupy the project site. District staff are now bringing the lease and other documents, including an NOE for the sublease, to the Board for approval. Below is a description of the documents.

 

Lease between the District and Health Sciences High and Middle College

In accordance with California Education Code section 47613, HSHMC will occupy 3910 University Avenue, with the District as the new owner/landlord. (Prior to the District's purchase of the property, HSHMC was already a tenant). HSHMC will occupy approximately 95 percent of the property (with existing tenant, Citibank to occupy the remainder). HSHMC will be responsible for all costs associated with repairs and maintenance of the building and parking garage, including landscaping and utilities. The term of the lease is 20 years commencing on January 16, 2019, with two options to extend for five additional years each.

 

Sublease between Health Sciences High and Middle College and Reality Changers

Reality Changers is an existing subtenant (of Workforce Partnership vacating on January 15, 2019) at 3910 University Avenue and has requested to remain at the property until construction is completed for their new facilities at Wilson/Central. Reality Changers will occupy the majority of the fourth floor at 3910 University Avenue and will be responsible for directly reimbursing HSHMC for their pro rata share of operating expenses. The term of the sublease is one year with an additional one year option to extend.

 

Second Amendment to Lease between San Diego Unified School District and Citibank

Citibank is an existing tenant at 3910 University Avenue and exercised an available option under the lease with the previous owner to remain at the property for an additional five years commencing on March 15, 2019. Citibank occupies 2,478 square feet on the first floor and will be responsible for paying rent to the District and directly reimbursing HSHMC for its pro rata share of operating expenses. This Second Amendment has a termination provision to allow Citibank to vacate the property at any time during this five-year renewal option period. Citibank will likely exercise the termination provision within the next two years.

 

Assignment of Operating Expenses for Citibank

As HSHMC will be responsible for payment of all building operating expenses and Citibank is a tenant of the District, this assignment is needed to provide for Citibank to reimburse HSHMC directly for its pro rata share of building operating expenses.

 

Assignment of Operating Expenses for Metro Villas Housing Partners

The parking garage at 3995 Polk Avenue is shared between the tenants of 3910 University Avenue and the neighboring residential development which is owned by Metro Villas Housing Partners (Metro Villas). Per the Shared Parking Agreement, Metro Villas is to pay a portion of the garage operating expenses. As HSHMC will be responsible for payment of all garage operating expenses, this assignment is needed to provide for Metro Villas to reimburse HSHMC directly for its share of garage operating expenses.

BACKGROUND: The District and Capella University have been partnering to deliver services in support of the Pupil Personnel Services credentialing regulations and the standards of the California Commission on Teacher Credentialing (CCTC). Through this partnership, Capella graduate students will receive on-site learning, supervision, and contact hours for their Practicum or Fieldwork experience. The duration of the Practicum or Fieldwork experience will be determined by the District Counseling and Guidance Department and Capella University; however, the Practicum (100 hours) will be completed within one calendar year, and Fieldwork experience (600 hours) will be completed within one calendar year at full-time (non-internship) OR two calendar years at part-time.

 

The duties of those completing a Practicum or Fieldwork experience will be determined by the District in accordance with the California Standards for the Counseling Profession; and will vary depending on available on-site opportunities. The list of duties to be completed by each are:

 

Practicum Duties (100 hours)

1. Peer counseling;

2. Personal and career assessment;

3. Individual or group personal counseling experience;

4. School-based programs serving parents and family members;

5. Community service programs serving children and families;

6. School-related experience (e.g. "shadowing" school counselors, observing classroom instruction, attending District and school-based meetings, becoming familiar with school-based community resources, etc.)

7. Increase familiarity of students with disabilities; Gifted and Talented programs; attend/observe IEP/504 meetings; assessment and evaluation activities; Common Core instructional activities; Student Study teams; master schedule activities; etc.

 

Fieldwork Duties (600 hours)

1. Continue to participate in any duties or activities listed under the practicum section;

2. Perform functions of school counselors in school counseling domains;

3. Work with diversity programs;

4. Work with the development and implementation of a program that addresses diversity issues;

5. Work with individuals and groups of a racial and ethnic background different from that of the candidate;

6. Gain experience at two different school settings: elementary, middle school, OR high school; and

7. Participate in group supervision throughout the Fieldwork experience.

 

Capella will ensure their students are aware of, and adhere to, District policies and administrative procedures (e.g. security clearances, health screenings, standards for health, safety, cooperation, ethical behavior, etc).

RECOMMENDATION: Ratification of First Amendment with Always Be Learning (ABL) to continue providing a school scheduling software platform at various District schools (SW-18-0236-25). The term of this Agreement remains September 27, 2017 through the completion of the project.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: Total not-to-exceed amount: $61,892.00. Budget string:  5593-73380-00-5842-1000-1110-01000-0000.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None. The first year was a pilot program. 

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND:  Last year Always Be Learning (ABL) partnered with the District to provide continuous school improvements in the master scheduling process, with the mutual interest in working closely together to create new and innovative tools around school scheduling. This was a pilot project at no cost to the district.  Based on the success of the program, it has been expanded to include Crawford, Morse, and San Diego high schools. This agreement will provide access to the ABL Master Scheduler platform, strategic planning, project management and ongoing check-ins, virtual coaching and email support for schedulers, platform set-up and on-boarding, data mapping and validation, phone support for IT teams, online knowledge base and documentation, and three days of on-site professional development. PowerSchool allows the sorting course requests to build the schedule. ABL allows deeper thinking about student need and designing structures to close gaps in achievement.
